# SclJet rowid point-lookup

A single-table `SELECT … WHERE rowid = K` or `WHERE <INTEGER PRIMARY KEY> = K` now seeks the row via
an O(log n) B-tree descent (`descendToLeaf`) instead of a full scan, then feeds the 0/1 found rows to
the same `finishRows` pipeline — so the result is byte-identical to a full scan (verified below for
hits, a miss, the rowid pseudo-column, the IPK column, and `COUNT(*)` over the seek). The seek is
overflow-safe: a row whose payload spills onto overflow pages falls back to the full scan
(exercised separately in `scljet-sql-rowid-seek-overflow`). Every result matches reference sqlite3
(verified out-of-band); locked across `[int, js]`.

[ByteSlice, SqliteValue, SqlInteger, SqlText, buildTableDatabase](std/scljet/index.ssc)
[queryImage, executeMutation, renderRows](std/scljet/sql.ssc)

```scalascript
def apply(db: ByteSlice, sql: String): ByteSlice =
  executeMutation(db, sql) match
    case Left(m) =>
      println(sql + " => ERR:" + m)
      db
    case Right(next) => next

def show(db: ByteSlice, sql: String): Unit =
  queryImage(db, sql) match
    case Left(m) => println(sql + " => ERR:" + m)
    case Right(rows) => println(sql + " => " + renderRows(rows).toString)

buildTableDatabase(512, 1, 1, "t", "CREATE TABLE t(id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY, name TEXT)",
  List(List(SqlInteger(1L), SqlText("seed")))) match
  case Left(error) => println("build-error:" + error.message)
  case Right(db0) =>
    val db1 = apply(db0, "DELETE FROM t")
    val db = apply(db1, "INSERT INTO t VALUES (5,'a'),(2,'b'),(9,'c'),(20,'d')")
    show(db, "SELECT id, name FROM t WHERE id = 9")
    show(db, "SELECT name FROM t WHERE id = 2")
    show(db, "SELECT id, name FROM t WHERE id = 7")
    show(db, "SELECT name FROM t WHERE rowid = 20")
    show(db, "SELECT id, name FROM t WHERE id = 5")
    show(db, "SELECT COUNT(*) FROM t WHERE id = 9")
    show(db, "SELECT COUNT(*) FROM t WHERE id = 7")
```
